# ANTI-SLOP STANDARD RULES (Cursor)

## PRINCIPLES
- Nothing redundant, generic, or purposeless.
- Eliminate slop: obvious comments, dead code, duplication.
- Comments only explain the "why".
- Do not invent APIs, structures, or concepts foreign to the code.

## MODES AND COMMANDS
anti-slop check <path>       # non-destructive inspection
anti-slop apply <path>       # applies safe fixes
anti-slop validate <path>    # validates types, routes, schemas

Flags:
--mode normal | backend | frontend | design
--auto-apply
--dry-run

## BACKEND RULES
- Clean and non-duplicated REST routes.
- A single HTTP client and a single DB client.
- Handlers <10 lines; logic in services.
- Mandatory Zod validation.
- Errors with uniform structure.
- ENV validated at startup.

## FRONTEND TECH RULES
- Server Components by default.
- `use client` only if essential.
- Tailwind without arbitrary classes.
- Images with width/height; lazy loading.
- Goals: LCP≤2.5s, INP≤200ms, CLS≤0.1.
- Accessibility: contrast ≥4.5.

## DESIGN RULES
- Colors only from tokens.
- Do not hardcode hex.
- Non-generic fonts without justification.
- Maximum 1–2 animations per view.

## PR RULES
- Destructive changes require human PR.
- API, DB, AUTH contracts or tokens require mandatory review.

--- FILE: .cursor/rules/anti-slop-nuclear.rules ---
# ANTI-SLOP NUCLEAR RULES (Cursor)

This file should only be used with:
anti-slop purge <path> --mode nuclear --destructive-open-pr

## PRINCIPLES
- Zero tolerance for redundancy.
- Zero unnecessary comments.
- Zero useless wrappers.
- Zero excessive structural depth.

## NUCLEAR ACTIONS
- Remove all comments that are not a "why" with a ticket.
- Remove every duplicated function or passive wrapper.
- Flatten structures: reduce nesting to maximum 2 levels.
- Split any function with multiple responsibilities.
- Delete files that serve only to organize without logic.
- Rename generic variables (data/info/result → semantic).
- Remove unused imports without asking.

## AUTOMATIC DELETE CRITERIA
If something:
- Has no explicit reason,
- Has no direct use,
- Does not provide immediate clarity,
- Or is more complex than necessary,

→ It is automatically deleted.

## RED FLAGS (IMMEDIATE ELIMINATION)
- Syntax comments.
- Commented-out code.
- Redundant try/catch blocks.
- Files that only re-export.
- Empty AI-style words ("robust", "seamless", etc.).
- Multiple returns without necessity.
